				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Kiting is running around with the Monster (mob) you want to kill following you but unable to catch you.  
<br />

<br />
You run far enough ahead of the mob so you can nuke (direct damage spell) or DoT (damage over time spell) it before it can catch up to you.  Using this method, you will eventually kill the mob or run out of mana.  
<br />
To make this possible, you should snare the mob, making it run slower.  
<br />
With the mob snared, you open the gap faster, allowing you to cast sooner.  You can also use slow casting spells when the mob is snared (your spells have a certain range, if the mob can close that range before you finish casting, it'll hit you which is what you're trying to avoid with kiting).
<br />

<br />
Quad-kiting is a variation where you kite 4 mobs at once.  Instead of killing one mob at a time, Area Effect spells are used to hit all 4 mobs at once.  This is usually done by Druids and Wizards.  Necros don't have suitable AE spells.
<br />

<br />
Fear kiting is a variation preferred by necros.  Instead of running away from the mob, we fear it and make it run away from us <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />   (sadly this doesn't work on mobs level 55+ as they are all immune to fear). 
<br />

<br />

<br />
If you do decide to kite, I would suggest you also get a SoW buff (Spirit of Wolf - makes you run faster)
<br />

<br />

<br />
Well.. those are the basics.. should give you an idea what kiting is and how to do it <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
