			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">There are a few styles of kiting:
<br />

<br />
Traditional Kiting:  Mob chases you, and you either nuke or dot it to death.  Much easier if you have a type of snare spell to slow the mobs running speed.
<br />

<br />
Root-n-rot (or root and cook):  Root the mob in one place and stack all kinds of dots on it.  Direct Damage spells and the DD portion of some dots will have a chance at breaking root.
<br />

<br />
Fear kiting:  Fear a mob and either stack dots on it or sick the pet on it.  Re-fear as necessary.
<br />

<br />
Aggro kiting:  Using a low level spell, you repeatedly cast it to get and keep aggro.  The mob will chase you while your pet (or group members' pets) attack it from behind.  Basically traditional kiting with a pet beating on it from behind.
<br />

<br />
Swarm kiting:  Bards used to do this until it was recently nerfed.  They would gather many, many mobs and run in cirlces playing their AE songs.  The mobs would be in range of the song but out of melee range.
<br />

<br />
Charm kiting:  Another bard style of kiting where you pull like four mobs.  You charm one of the mobs and the other three will beat it almost to death.  You break charm and dot the mob to death, then charm another one and repeat.  The cast time of the charm spell make this less feasible for the casting charm classes.
<br />

<br />
Quad kiting (can be 2 to 4 mobs):  Gather the mobs.  Run in circles to get the mobs on top of one another.  Use the AE spells to hit all the mobs.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
